Packet 3: Relationships among scales

Last updated 2018-04-07

This is an exploration of the relationships among scales included in Packet 3.

Correlation matrix

First, let’s look at the overall correlationships among scores on the various scales included in Packet 3. (These are individual participant-level correlations):

Setting row names on a tibble is deprecated.

From this, we see that several of the scales included in Packet 3 were positively correlated with each other. Unsurprisingly, many of the “dualism” subscales were positively correlated. But we also see some intriguing correlations among the inner speech, hearing events, and encoding style scales - and, surprisingly, endorsement of metaphors of mind? Maybe also some correaltions with uncontrollability and need to control, as well as other metacognition subscales…? Let’s check these relationships out in more detail!

Note: There is a separate document for grappling with the “dualism” scale on its own.

Inner speech and hearing events

Here’s a test for the overall correlation between inner speech as measured by the Hardy/Bentall scale, and “hearing events” as measured by the Posey & Losch scale:


    Pearson's product-moment correlation

data:  inner speech and hearing events
t = 11.851, df = 499, p-value < 2.2e-16
alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 0.3973600 0.5343159
sample estimates:
      cor 
0.4686493

Inner speech (as measured by Hardy/Bentall) was significantly positively correlated with reported hearing events (\(r\) = 0.47, \(p\) = <0.001), accounting for approximately 22% of the variance in reported hearing events.

Now let’s take a look at what’s going on in each site with a regression analysis:

b se t p
baserate (overall) 5.21 0.15 35.28 <0.001
baserate (ghana vs. overall) -0.92 0.29 -3.14 0.002
baserate (thailand vs. overall) 0.07 0.29 0.24 0.809
baserate (china vs. overall) -0.67 0.30 -2.25 0.025
baserate (vanuatu vs. overall) 1.68 0.30 5.55 <0.001
HB inner speech (overall) 0.24 0.02 10.82 <0.001
HB inner speech (ghana vs. overall) 0.11 0.04 2.82 0.005
HB inner speech (thailand vs. overall) -0.08 0.04 -1.95 0.052
HB inner speech (china vs. overall) 0.06 0.05 1.23 0.218
HB inner speech (vanuatu vs. overall) -0.06 0.05 -1.36 0.174

These results indicate that there was a significant positive relationship between inner speech (as measured by Hardy/Bentall) and reported hearing events-like events, collapsing across sites (\(b\) = 0.24, \(p\) = <0.001). The relationship between inner voice and hearing events was somewhat stronger among participants in Ghana (\(b\) = 0.11, \(p\) = 0.005).

Note also that this test picked up on some differences in the baserates for reporting hearing events-like events (controlling for the relationships described above): Participants in Ghana and China seem to have reported fewer than average of these kinds of events (Ghana: \(b\) = -0.92, \(p\) = 0.002; China: \(b\) = -0.67, \(p\) = 0.025), while participants in Vanuatu seem to have reported more than average (Vanuatu: \(b\) = 1.68, \(p\) = <0.001).

Inner speech and encoding style

Here’s a test for the overall correlation between inner speech as measured by the Hardy/Bentall scale, and “encoding style” (which seems like a kind of hallucination-like event) as measured by the Lewicki scale:


    Pearson's product-moment correlation

data:  inner speech and encoding style
t = 9.8132, df = 498, p-value < 2.2e-16
alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 0.3263698 0.4735158
sample estimates:
      cor 
0.4025399

Inner speech (as measured by Hardy/Bentall) was significantly positively correlated with reported encoding style (\(r\) = 0.4, \(p\) = <0.001), accounting for approximately 16% of the variance in reported encoding style.

Now let’s take a look at what’s going on in each site with a regression analysis:

b se t p
baserate (overall) 14.15 0.37 38.18 <0.001
baserate (ghana vs. overall) 2.30 0.73 3.14 0.002
baserate (thailand vs. overall) -0.10 0.73 -0.14 0.888
baserate (china vs. overall) -2.60 0.75 -3.45 <0.001
baserate (vanuatu vs. overall) -1.62 0.76 -2.12 0.034
HB inner speech (overall) 0.53 0.06 9.41 <0.001
HB inner speech (ghana vs. overall) 0.16 0.10 1.61 0.109
HB inner speech (thailand vs. overall) -0.23 0.10 -2.26 0.024
HB inner speech (china vs. overall) -0.04 0.13 -0.29 0.769
HB inner speech (vanuatu vs. overall) 0.00 0.12 -0.01 0.991

These results indicate that there was a significant positive relationship between inner speech (as measured by Hardy/Bentall) and reported encoding style events, collapsing across sites (\(b\) = 0.53, \(p\) = <0.001). The relationship between inner voice and encoding style was somewhat weaker among participants in Thailand (\(b\) = -0.23, \(p\) = 0.024).

Note also that this test picked up on some differences in the baserates for reporting encoding style (controlling for the relationships described above): In contrast to the “hearing events” above, participants in Vanuatu seem to have reported fewer than average of these kinds of events, as did participants in China (Vanuatu: \(b\) = -1.62, \(p\) = 0.034; China: \(b\) = -2.60, \(p\) = <0.001), while participants in Ghana seem to have reported more than average (Ghana: \(b\) = 2.30, \(p\) = 0.002).

Many aspects of metacognition were significantly positively correlated with inner speech (as measured by Hardy/Bentall) was significantly positively correlated with reported encoding style; in fact, the only one that wasn’t “significant” was the lack of cognitive confidence (\(r\) = 0.08, \(p\) = 0.071).

The (numerically) strongest relationship was with cognitive self-consciousness (\(r\) = 0.33, \(p\) = <0.001), accounting for approximately 11% of the variance in reported inner speech.

Now let’s take a closer look at this particular relationship by looking at what’s going on in each site with a regression analysis:

b se t p
baserate (overall) 3.83 0.29 13.3 <0.001

cog. self-consciousness (vanuatu vs. overall) 0.03 0.16 0.2 0.840

These results indicate that there was a significant positive relationship between cognitive self-consciousness and inner speech (as measured by Hardy/Bentall), collapsing across sites (\(b\) = 0.51, \(p\) = <0.001). The relationship between this aspect of metacognition and inner speech was stronger among participants in Ghana (\(b\) = 0.69, \(p\) = <0.001), and weaker among participants in Thailand (\(b\) = -0.34, \(p\) = 0.027).

Note also that this test picked up on some differences in the baserates for inner speech (controlling for the relationships described above): Participants in China and (perhaps) Thailand seem to have reported fewer than average of these kinds of events (China: \(b\) = -1.90, \(p\) = <0.001; Thailand: \(b\) = -1.13, \(p\) = 0.048), while participants in Ghana and (perhaps) Vanuatu seem to have reported more than average (Ghana: \(b\) = 2.40, \(p\) = <0.001; Vanuatu: \(b\) = 1.12, \(p\) = 0.050).
